jXlvGx8bWpSeo ]
Biggest takeaways:
The design handoff is dead=E2=80=94replaced by continuous sync. Instead of =
designers creating comprehensive design packages with every state documente=
d, AI enables bidirectional flow between Figma and code. Pull production co=
de into Figma to see what actually exists, make changes in Figma, then push=
 those changes directly back to code. No more version-final-final-v3.
Direct manipulation still beats prompting for precision. While AI can gener=
ate designs from prompts, dragging elements around in Figma remains the gol=
d standard for fine-tuning. As Gui notes, =E2=80=9CNo one wants to prompt f=
or the exact hex code or shade of yellow=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s just=
 easier to use the color picker and eyeball it.
Use Figma=E2=80=99s MCP to keep design files current with production. The b=
iggest problem in design-code workflows is drift=E2=80=94production gets ah=
ead of Figma, or Figma contains dreams that never shipped. With MCP, you ca=
n programmatically pull any production state into Figma, ensuring that desi=
gners always work from what actually exists.
Turn your engineering wiki into executable skills. Every team has that onbo=
arding page: =E2=80=9CThis is what you do before pushing a PR.=E2=80=9D Ale=
x built a /ship skill that automatically runs pre-flight checks, pushes to =
Git, monitors CI, and even fixes minor lint issues=E2=80=94up to five times=
 with a one-hour timeout. Take every SOP and make it a skill.
Structure your codebase for AI assistance. Alex spends 20% to 30% of his ti=
me optimizing code structure so AI can accomplish more with less. This isn=
=E2=80=99t about writing better code for humans; it=E2=80=99s about making =
your codebase more legible to AI agents so each prompt delivers better resu=
lts.
